{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 MonkeyBars Reaper Scripts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The URL to import in ReaPack is https://github.com/MonkeyBars3k/ReaScripts/raw/master/index.xml.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Superglue\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Background\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two main ways to consolidate selected items on a track natively in Reaper: {\b Glue} and {\b Groups}. Both have disadvantages.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Glue} is permanent: once you glue items together, you cannot make edits later without cutting again. This can be problematic as you may wish make any number of changes to the glued items (such as make the sound of a kick drum's tail longer, etc.). You cannot do this using Glue, a "destructive" edit.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The other option is to {\b Group} items. This works well if you simply want to move items around or select multiple items by clicking one item; however, you cannot use many other benefits of a single Reaper item, such as quickly looping, take envelopes & fx, etc. Grouping can also become confusing because Groups are highlighted in green around the items, but {\i not} around the boundary of the group itself. Groups can be unwieldy to work with in many musical contexts, such as a four-bar repetition, and they can create visual clutter.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Superglue} aims to address the shortcomings of both Glue and Groups, restore the convenient functionality already present in items (looping, timestretching, and much more) by placing selected items in a new container item called a {\b Superitem} \u8211- {\i and} provide users the convenience of {\b audio item pooling}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 How to use\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b To Superglue items}, simply select items and trigger the {\b MB_Superglue Glue} script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To change the contents of your Superitem, the {\b Edit} script "opens" the created Superitem, restoring the contained items once again.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To reglue, just use one of the Glue or Smart Action scripts again.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\b Unglue} scripts restore the contained items to their state from before that pool's last Superglue (i.e., irreversibly restore the contained items in the Superitem), severing connection to their former Pool. If you Glue after Unglue, the resulting Superitem will be in a new Pool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\b Glue/Edit & Glue/Unglue Smart Action} scripts intelligently determine which action is required based on your item selection!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Features\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Provides the missing {\b nondestructive/reversible Glue} feature in Reaper!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab A.k.a.: Glue Groups, Item Containers, Container Items, Pooled Item Boxes, Pooled Audio Items\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Provides the missing {\b pooled audio items} feature in Reaper!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Superitem copies are {\b pooled by default}. Editing and regluing one Superitem {\b updates all instances} in that Pool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Run the script to {\b Remove Superitem from current Pool} to place a Superitem on its own new Pool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Disable Superitem pooling by enabling the option to {\b Remove Superitem siblings from Pool on Glue}. Careful: this removes formerly copied Superitems from their pools. If you want a mix of pooled and unpooled Superitems, it's recommended to run the script to Remove Superitem from Pool manually as needed.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Supports {\b nesting Superitems} inside {\i other} Superitems! When you update the nested Superitem, Superglue finds any Superitem that contains it and updates it as well. There is no limit in the code as to how many times you can nest Superitems \u8211- tested with 20 levels of nesting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Superglue has its own script options that can be selected by the user. Just run the script to {\b Open the options window} and try them out. Scripts are also supplied to toggle (On-Off) or cycle (3+ states) options.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab You can {\b toggle Expansion to time selection} in the options window.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Tips\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Using just the pooled audio item feature:} Feel free to Superglue a {\i single audio item} and make copies of that! Since every Superitem you copy is a pooled audio item, all you need to ensure all the copies stay updated is Edit any one of the pooled Superitems and reglue (Glue again). If you ever want to remove a Superitem from its pool and place it in its own new pool, just run the {\b Remove Superitem from current Pool} script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Using just the container feature:} The most basic application of Superglue is to treat a Superitem as a container item that can be edited easily later, i.e. a more convenient way to group items and apply settings to them as a whole.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Check out {\b all the scripts} that get installed when you sync the ReaPack repo. There are some very useful utilities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Make sure to examine the {\b options window} which enables numerous configurations for various use cases. Options are saved in your install's .ini file.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Contained Items can extend beyond your Superitem edges, enabling an {\b extradimensional pocket to hide items in your project} without having to hide a track or add muted items anywhere. (Run the script to {\b Display Superglue item info} to reveal how many contained items are "in" a Superitem.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab While Superglue does add a default Pool number prefix to Superitem take names, you may end up changing the name. In this and other cases, it's useful to open up the {\b Superglue item info window} to see its Parent Pool ID and other relevant Superglue data.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Requirements\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Requires {\b Reaper v6.43} or newer\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Requires {\b SWS Plugin Extension} and {\b js_ReaScript_API Plugin Extension}\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Warnings\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Audio sources\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Be {\i very} careful if you want to {\b Clean current project directory} after Supergluing \u8211- you could lose contained items' audio, since at that point those "items" aren't included in the project proper \u8211- they are only represented in the project data (state chunks). If you want to clean your project, you ought to Edit an Instance from every Pool, clean, then Reglue them all.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Stay aware of the state of your Superitems whenever {\b editing audio externally}. If you're destructively editing a contained item's audio source, or for example editing a subproject which is present as a contained item in a Superitem, such items' direct parent must be in Edit mode ("open") during your external audio source edits, or their ancestors (parent, grandparent, etc. Superitems) won't be updated.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 MIDI\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Currently only {\b MIDI on virtual instrument tracks} is supported.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab To create {\b MIDI Superitems}, the script uses "Apply track FX as new take" on each item to get an audio take. When you Edit, the audio take is removed and just the original MIDI take is made active.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Editing Superitems\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When you Edit a Superitem, a {\b special white region}, the Sizing Region, is automatically created so you can alter the Superitem's eventual edge positions after Reglue. Try not to remove this Sizing Region since its bounds match the edges of the Edited Superitem. If a Sizing Region does get deleted, when you attempt to reglue Superglue will prompt you to create a new region at the edges of the Restored Items.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Be careful Editing a parent Superitem {\b near project start}. If a child Superitem would extend before project start, its source offset will adjust automatically so its audio is in the right place, but regluing could affect its sibling pooled Superitems in unexpected ways.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Remember that {\b restored items can extend beyond the size of your Superitem} on Edit. Stay aware of content in tracks (such as items, track envelopes, etc.) nearby.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab It's not recommended to {\b Edit Superitems with adjusted take playrate} because the Contained Items are at their playrate at last Superglue, so they won't match up to the audio in the Superitem with adjusted take playrate. Best either to do your playrate work on the Contained Items in the first place, or Edit a Sibling at 1.0 playrate.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Propagation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab There are numerous options that control how Superglue propagates changes to the Edited Superitem to its Siblings and Ancestors on reglue. Pay close attention to how these are set, or you might fall prey to unwanted changes downstream. If your needs often vary, set Propagation options to "Ask".\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Nesting\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab With the option to {\b Remove Superitem siblings from Pool on Glue} enabled, nested Siblings will be removed from the Edited pool but Siblings nested in Parents from any one Pool will all share the same new Pool.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Superitem configuration\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Multiple takes on Superitems are not supported. If you try to Edit a Superitem with multiple takes, you'll be prompted to explode them or cancel.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Set the {\b item mix behavior} on your items/tracks/project very carefully, as that affects how your items glue. Unfortunately, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://forum.cockos.com/showthread.php?p=2525910"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
the ReaScript API does not allow setting this mode directly
}}}
 yet.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When using copies of Superitems, you can't Superglue a copy of itself inside itself, as that would cause an {\b infinite recursion} and implode the universe in a Big Crunch type event. (This actually happened during dev a few times but I was safe inside my pocket microverse and simply undid reality afterwards.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Superglue uses item notes to set background images for easy recognition of Superitems and contained items. Careful: {\b The background image will overwrite any item notes you already have on your glued items.} Just disable this feature in the script options window or with the included script if you don't like it for any reason.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Glossary\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Ancestor}: A Superitem in which another Superitem or other Superitems are nested \u8211- parents, grandparents, etc. are ancestors.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Child}: A Superitem which is nested (superglued) inside another Superitem (its parent)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Contained items}: Items whose data ("state chunks" in ReaScript parlance) are referenced in a Pool's data\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Descendant}: A Superitem nested one or more levels inside another Superitem \u8211- children, grandchildren, etc. are descendants.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Edit}: Restore a Superitem to its "contained" items reversibly/nondestructively, maintaining the ability to Reglue them and retain Superitem properties and update its Pool Siblings\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Instance}: Superitem from a given Pool\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Nest}: Superglue a Superitem into or inside another Superitem\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Parent}: The Superitem in which another Superitem is directly nested\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Pool}: A group of Siblings that update each other if Edited\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Reglue}: Run a Superglue Glue script on items restored from a Superitem (i.e. Edit mode)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Restored items}: Contained items which reappear after running an Edit or Unglue script on a Superitem\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Sibling}: Pooled copy of a Superitem \u8211- Edit any Sibling, and all its Sibling and Ancestor Superitems get updated as well.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Sizing Region}: Special white region created by Superglue upon Editing a Superitem to alert user to the Edited Superitem's bounds and make it easy to resize on Reglue\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Smart Action}: Superglue script that tries to guess the user's intention from the item selection \u8211- sometimes you'll be prompted for an action choice or warned that none can be determined automagically.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Superitem}: The resulting "container item" after Supergluing \u8211- really just a Reaper item with some data stored in it and which is connected to the Pool's data stored in the project\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Unglue}: Restore a Superitem into its Contained Items irreversibly/destructively, deleting any connection to their pool and any of the former Superitem's properties\sa180\par}
